Airport.Name: Fort Collins Loveland
Report.Status: the student pilot's premature flare resulting in the loss of aircraft control.

Airport.Name: Malcolm McKinnon Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for wind conditions.  A factor in the accident was the wind gust.

Airport.Name: Kodiak
Report.Status: The failure of company maintenance personnel to ensure that the airplane's nose baggage door latching mechanism was properly configured and maintained, resulting in an inadvertent opening of the nose baggage door in flight. Contributing to the accident were the lack of information and guidance available to the operator and pilot regarding procedures to follow should a baggage door open in flight and an inadvertent aerodynamic stall.

Airport.Name: Hernando County
Report.Status: A deer darting into the path of the airplane during the landing roll.
A loss of engine power due to inadequate maintenance inspection resulting in a worn throttle housing going undetected and failing.

Airport.Name: Philbrick Mountain
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing.  Contributing to the accident was the pilot's selection of an unsuitable landing area.

Airport.Name: THUNDERHAWK FIELD
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control.
The pilot's improper preflight and in-flight planning which resulted in a loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion.

Airport.Name: Pine Bluffs
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain control of the airplane. Contributing factors in this accident were the unfavorable wind and the snow bank.

Airport.Name: St Petersburg-Clearwater Int'l
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain airspeed while maneuvering for approach to land. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's operation of the airplane above the design gross weight.

Airport.Name: Placerville Airport
Report.Status: The collapse of the right main landing gear during landing for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: T W Spear Memorial Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to attain the proper touchdown point.
A loss of engine power due to carburetor icing conditions and the failure of the pilot to use the correct amount of carburetor heat for the existing conditions.

Airport.Name: Dekalb-Peachtree Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the pilot-in-command to maintain directional control of the airplane during landing.

Airport.Name: Bethel
Report.Status: The pilot's selection of unsuitable terrain for landing. Contributing to the accident were snow-covered terrain, blowing snow and flat lighting conditions.
The failure of both pilots to see and avoid the other airplane.
The student pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during the landing roll.  Contributing to the accident were the snow-covered runway and the gusty wind conditions.

Airport.Name: St. Louis/Downtown
Report.Status: Maintenance personnel's improper replacement of the landing gear leg brace assembly which subsequently failed to keep the landing gear in the locked position.

Airport.Name: Beaver Marsh State Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate in-flight planning/decision to land on a snow covered runway without first determining the depth of the snow.

Airport.Name: Carroll County Regional
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare.

Airport.Name: Canon Ranch Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain sufficient airspeed while maneuvering which resulted in a stall.

Airport.Name: Dawson Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing roll out.

Airport.Name: Picayune Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's misjudgement of the landing flare resulting in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Palo Alto Airport
Report.Status: Loss of engine power during the takeoff initial climb due to lack of compression to a cylinder.

Airport.Name: Lindsay Municipal
Report.Status: The flight instructor's failure to maintain control of the airplane, which resulted in an inadvertent stall while maneuvering.

Airport.Name: RICHARD LLOYD JONES JR
Report.Status: The owner of the parking surface's failure to ensure that the parking surface was clear of hazards to taxiing airplanes and the pilot's failure to ensure a safe taxi route in unfamiliar surroundings.
The pilot's failure to maintain aircraft control after flying into clouds.

Airport.Name: Austin Bergstrom International
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain control of the airplane while parked on the ramp with the engine running.

Airport.Name: St. Augustine
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to adhere to the controller's takeoff instruction.  Contributing to the incident was the controller's failure to properly monitor the flight, and the controller's decision to perform lesser duty priorities during the takeoff roll.

Airport.Name: San Antonio International
Report.Status: Separation of the turbocharger exhaust stack, which resulted in a loss of engine power.

The pilot's continued visual flight into an area of known instrument meteorological conditions in an airplane not equipped for instrument flight, and his failure to maintain control of the airplane while maneuvering at low altitude.

The pilot's intentional low altitude flight and his failure to maintain clearance from the static wire.  Contributing to the accident were the static wire, the partial loss of engine power due to propeller vibration, and the muddy field in which the forced landing was made.

Airport.Name: St. Louis Downtown Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructor's failure to correct for proper runway alignment during final approach and his failure to maintain aircraft control during his subsequent go-around.  Contributing to the accident was the dual-student's failure to properly align with the runway centerline during final approach and the dark night.

Airport.Name: Arlington Municipal
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper landing flare resulting in a hard landing.  Contributing to the accident were the gusty surface winds and the student pilot's inadequate preflight planning.
The loss of engine power for undetermined reasons.  Contributing factors were the lack of suitable terrain for the forced landing and dark night conditions.

Airport.Name: Logan-Cache Airport
Report.Status: The dual-student's excessive brake application, and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision of the flight.
The pilot's delay in aborting the landing.
Pilot's inaccurate fuel management resulting in fuel exhaustion.

Airport.Name: DAVID WAYNE HOOKS MEMORIAL
Report.Status: Failure of the pilot to ensure that the fuel system was purged of water prior to flight.  Contributing to the severity of injuries was the lack of shoulder restraints.

Airport.Name: Biggin Hill Airport
Report.Status: Failure of the pilot to maintain a safe clearance from the terrain while manuevering for the landing surface.

Airport.Name: Sky Ranch Airport at Carefree
Report.Status: The collapse of the landing gear during landing rollout for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Livermore Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for the crosswind condition and failure to maintain directional control during landing.

Airport.Name: Gainesville Regional Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper flare.

Airport.Name: Orlando International Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's inadequate recovery from a bounced landing.
The pilot not maintaining directional control during the landing and the ground loop the pilot encountered.  A factor was the crosswind.

Airport.Name: Kalispell City Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain alignment with the runway while landing and executing a go-around.

Airport.Name: Arnold Field
Report.Status: The flight instructor's inadequate remedial action. Contributing to the accident was the student pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Dekalb-Peachtree
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Perry-Houston County Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's inadequate compensation for wind conditions during landing. Contributing to the accident were the gusting winds.

Airport.Name: Greater Cumberland Regional
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain the proper approach course for undetermined reasons.

Airport.Name: Cochise County Airport
Report.Status: A loss of engine power while on final approach due to multiple grounding faults in the ignition system as a result of poor ignition system maintenance.

Airport.Name: Poplar Grove Airport
Report.Status: The left wing skin "fabric patch" separated from the wing ribs and spars for an undetermined reason.

Airport.Name: Canyonlands Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the tail wheel-equipped airplane during the flare/touchdown phase of a three-point landing.
The loss of propeller thrust due to the unseating of an internal propeller hub bushing. Contributing to the accident was the manufacturer's inadequate procedure to secure the bushing.
The pilot's failure to maintain adequate airspeed to prevent a stall while maneuvering, which resulted in an uncontrolled descent and collision with terrain.

Airport.Name: Quincy Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate in-flight decision by failing to refuel, resulting in fuel exhaustion and the loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: GILA BEND MUNI
Report.Status: The flight crew's inadvertent retraction of the landing gear during the landing roll, and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision of the flight.

Airport.Name: Riverside Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain airspeed and aircraft control, resulting in an aerodynamic stall.

Airport.Name: TRUCKEE-TAHOE
Report.Status: The pilot's continued operation with a known mechanical problem and failure to maintain directional control.

Airport.Name: Vero Beach Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during an aborted takeoff.
The pilot's inadequate compensation for wind conditions, and his failure to obtain/maintain directional control. Contributing factors were a crosswind and a snow bank.

Airport.Name: Mark Anton Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Mallory Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to obtain a proper touchdown point. Contributing to the accident was the windshear as reported by the pilot.

Airport.Name: Norwood Memorial Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the flightcrew to maintain directional control of the airplane.

Airport.Name: CENTRE MUNI
Report.Status: The pilot's improper landing flare, resulting in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Chandler Municipal
Report.Status: The student pilot's delay in initiating the go-around, and the flight instructor's inadequate supervision of the flight and delayed remedial action. Contributing to the accident were the momentary failure of the engine to respond, the failure of both the student and the instructor to adhere to the operator's procedures, and the rough/uneven terrain.
The flight instructor's inadequate evaluation of  the weather conditions. Contributing to the accident was an inadvertent stall/mush.

Airport.Name: Stinson Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain airspeed during the landing flare which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Takotna
Report.Status: The pilot's selection of unsuitable terrain for takeoff.

Airport.Name: Fort Lauderdale Executive
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during recovery from a bounced landing.
The pilot's failure to avoid the transmission line.  A contributing factor was the pilot's decision to perform a low-level maneuver.

Airport.Name: Charlottesville-Albemarle
Report.Status: The pilot's improper engine starting procedures.

Airport.Name: Richmond International Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: LAFAYETTE REGIONAL
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain aircraft control for undetermined reasons.  Contributing to the accident were the prevailing clouds, rain, and turbulence.

Airport.Name: Spartanburg Downtown Memorial
Report.Status: The pilot's encounter with wake turbulence during approach as a result of his inadequate in-flight planning.
The pilots inadvertent flight into flat light/whiteout conditions over snow-covered terrain.

Airport.Name: Richfield Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot's improper use of the flight controls and failure to maintain directional control.

Airport.Name: Okeechobee County Airport

On August 26, 2008, about 1100 local time, a Cessna 172, Ecuadorian registration HC-BKY, registered to an operated by Wings of Hope Incorporated, as a medical transport flight, crashed following a loss of engine power, while in cruise flight to Rio Amazonas Airport, Pastaza, Ecuador. Visual meteorological conditions prevailed, and no flight plan was filed. The airplane was substantial damage. The private-rated pilot and passenger received serious injuries. 

According to information obtained from the Ecuadorian Subdireccion de Aviacion Civil, the pilot reported total loss of engine power, while in cruise flight. He conducted an emergency landing, and crashed into trees.

This investigation is under the jurisdiction of the Government of Ecuador. Any further information can be obtained from:

Direccion General de Aviacion Civil
Buenos Aires 149 Y 10 de Agusto
P.O. Box 2077
Quito, Republica del Ecuador

Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate preflight inspection, which resulted in his failure to note the water in the fuel tank due to condensation, which subsequently shut down the engine in flight. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's self-induced pressure to expedite the departure.
A partial loss of engine power due to carburetor icing, which the pilot could not correct by applying carburetor heat because the movement of the carburetor heat control arm was restricted.

Airport.Name: San Antonio Internationsal
Report.Status: The pilots misjudgment of the landing speed and the runway distance remaining and his delay in applying the brakes, which resulted in an overrun.

Airport.Name: Blue Grass Airport
Report.Status: The rupture of the landing gears hydraulic pressure hose, which resulted in the depletion of all of the hydraulic fluid, and the inability of the landing gear to raise or lower. Contributing to the accident was the installation of an unapproved hydraulic hose by unknown maintenance personnel.

Airport.Name: Quad City International
Report.Status: The student pilot's misjudgment of the landing flare, which resulted in a bounced landing.
The fatigue failure of an improperly installed nipple in the oil system of a supplemental type certificate-installed supercharger, which resulted in a complete loss of engine oil during cruise climb.

Airport.Name: Knox County Regional Airport
Report.Status: The vehicle driver's failure to verify that the runway was not occupied by an airplane before crossing the runway, which resulted in the vehicle being struck by a departing airplane, and the pilot's continued takeoff with flight control damage, which subsequently resulted in an aerodynamic stall and spin at low altitude.

Airport.Name: Savannah/HHI International
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control while operating in night, instrument meteorological conditions, due to spatial disorientation.

Airport.Name: Poplar Grove Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain directional control of the airplane while landing.

Airport.Name: Simsbury Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain clearance from terrain while performing a night visual approach to an airport. Contributing to the accident were the dark night and the pilot's lack of recent experience flying at night.

Airport.Name: San Rafael Airport
Report.Status: The loss of engine power during initial climb for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Red Oak Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The loss of control while landing due to the solo student pilot's delay to execute a go-around and his improper control inputs during a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Hillsdale Minucipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from terrain during a straight-in night visual flight rules approach to land in hazy weather conditions. Contributing to the accident were the pilot's lack of recent night flying experience, the nonfunctional precision approach path indicator system on the selected runway, and the inaccurate Kollsman setting in the altimeter.
The flight instructor, while demonstrating a water landing to the pilot receiving instruction, did not maintain proper alignment with the landing surface, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Van Nuys
Report.Status: A partial loss of engine power during cruise flight due to fatigue fractures of two crankshaft gear teeth from corrosion pitting, which resulted in an off-airport forced landing and collision with obstacles on the ground.

The pilot's failure to maintain clearance with terrain while maneuvering in a remote mountainous region. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's improper decision to traverse the remote mountainous area in high-density altitude conditions with the airplane near its maximum gross weight. Contributing to the delay in the search and rescue (SAR) was the lack of a 406-MHz ELT signal, which would have allowed SAR responders to initiate a more timely search and find the accident site more quickly.
The pilots decision to continue the flight into an area of extreme weather, which led to the in-flight encounter with a thunderstorm and structural failure of the wings and tail.

Airport.Name: Capital Region IAP
Report.Status: A loss of engine power due to the loss of fuel flow through the airplane's fuel tank selector valve.

Airport.Name: PRIVATE
Report.Status: The pilots failure to monitor, recognize, and identify obstacles on approach to landing, which resulted in an inadvertent collision with power lines. Contributing to the accident was the pilots expectation and assumption that there were no above-ground power lines in the area.
The total loss of engine power as a result of a fractured compressor turbine blade due to fatigue cracking.

Airport.Name: Collin County Regional
Report.Status: The pilots inadequate flare, which resulted in a hard nosewheel landing.

Airport.Name: Kahului Airport
Report.Status: The noninstrument-rated pilots spatial disorientation and subsequent failure to maintain airplane control while operating over water in dark night conditions with reduced visibility due to rain in the area.

Airport.Name: Stanly County Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to remain clear of the airplanes rotating propeller.

Airport.Name: Rochester International

Airport.Name: Mekoryuk

Airport.Name: Joliet Regional
Report.Status: An in-flight loss of control and impact with terrain for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Easton/Newnam Field

Airport.Name: Flying Cloud

Airport.Name: Houston Southwest Airport
Report.Status: The loss of engine power during initial climb for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the engine did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

The pilot's inadequate preflight planning, which resulted in fuel exhaustion and a subsequent total loss of power in both engines during cruise flight. Contributing to the accident was the pilots use of prescription and illicit drugs, which likely impaired his judgment.

Airport.Name: Mc Allen Miller International
Report.Status: A loss of engine power due to carburetor icing.

Airport.Name: Chiloquin State Airport
Report.Status: The flight instructors failure to maintain airplane control during a landing on a snow-covered runway.

Airport.Name: Walker County Airport

Airport.Name: Mishawaka Pilots Club Airport
Report.Status: The pilots improper flare, which resulted in a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Oceano County Airport

Report.Status: The student pilot's inadequate landing flare and lack of remedial actions, which resulted in a hard bounced landing.

Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain control of the airplane during an aborted takeoff.

Airport.Name: Person County Airport
Report.Status: The pilots excessive use of wheel brakes while turning off the runway after landing resulting in a noseover.

Airport.Name: Henderson-Oxford Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots improper flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Ankeny Regional Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Friday Harbor
Report.Status: A collision with a bird while on the downwind leg of the traffic pattern.

Airport.Name: Carson City
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain aircraft control after an encounter with downdrafts while flying over mountainous terrain.

Airport.Name: Abbeville
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to properly secure the airplane before hand starting the engine and the failure of the brass tie down hook.

Airport.Name: RENO/TAHOE INTL
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control during descent while operating in instrument meteorological conditions.
The loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because the engine examination did not reveal any malfunctions or failures that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Auburn Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control during approach to landing, which resulted in an inadvertent stall and subsequent spin.

Airport.Name: DeKalb-Peachtree Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate preflight planning, which resulted in the airplane being loaded in excess of its maximum gross weight at an aft center of gravity for a takeoff with a quartering tailwind and high-density altitude conditions, all of which degraded the airplanes climb performance and led to the airplane exceeding its critical angle-of-attack and experiencing an aerodynamic stall.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll which resulted in a collision with a tree.

Airport.Name: Hendricks County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot not maintaining directional control of the airplane during the landing roll resulting in the ground loop.

Air.carrier: CAMPBELL ASSOCIATES AT CURTISS AERO INC
Report.Status: The pilot's loss of control due to spatial disorientation in instrument meteorological conditions, which resulted in an exceedance of the airplane's design stress limitations, and a subsequent in-flight breakup.

Airport.Name: Emporia Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to lower the landing gear prior to landing.

Airport.Name: Kern Valley Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll in gusty wind conditions.

Airport.Name: Middle Georgia Regional
Report.Status: A total loss of engine power due to oil starvation for reasons that could not be determined due to extensive postcrash fire and heat damage to the engine components.

Airport.Name: Page Municipal Airport
Report.Status: A loss of engine power during cruise flight due to fuel exhaustion. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's improper fuel planning.

Airport.Name: Brevard Airport
Report.Status: The cylinder manufacturer's misalignment of the exhaust valve guides in the No. 2 cylinder during manufacture, which resulted in the exhaust valve sticking and the pushrod breaking and the subsequent total loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Joseph Y Resnick Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's inadequate preflight planning and failure to maintain clearance from rising terrain, which resulted in controlled flight into terrain.

Airport.Name: Lake Brooks Seaplane
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate airspeed control during a glassy water landing, which resulted in an excessive sink rate, and a hard landing.
The pilots inadequate preflight planning, which resulted in fuel exhaustion and a subsequent total loss of engine power.

Airport.Name: Phoenix Deer Valley Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the pilots in both aircraft to maintain adequate visual lookout in a known training area where multiple aircraft frequently operated, which resulted in a midair collision.

Airport.Name: Concord Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilots delayed remedial action following a loss of directional control during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Millinocket Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots failure to maintain directional control during landing.

Airport.Name: Bryant Field Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's distracted attention while on final approach which resulted in his failure to maintain adequate airspeed and subsequent loss of aircraft control.

Airport.Name: Skagit Regional Airport
Report.Status: The failure of the rudder bar assembly during landing due to a fatigue crack. Contributing to the accident was the failure of maintenance personnel to perform an adequate inspection of the rudder bar assembly.

Airport.Name: Standard Field
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to use carburetor heat during the approach to landing, which resulted in carburetor icing and a partial loss of engine power during a subsequent initial climb.

Airport.Name: Boone County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot did not maintain control of the airplane during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Oakland County International
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to maintain aircraft control during the takeoff and his interference with the flight instructor's ability to provide remedial action.

Airport.Name: Chiloquin State Airport
Report.Status: The pilots unstabilized approach and use of an excessive speed at touchdown, which resulted in a loss of directional control during the landing and a subsequent runway excursion.
The pilot's failure to maintain aircraft control during takeoff.

Airport.Name: Nervino Airport
Report.Status: The pilots decision to takeoff from an area off the runway surface which resulted in a collision with an object.

The pilot's failure to maintain airplane control while attempting to clear a mountain pass in turbulent conditions at a high density altitude, which resulted in the airplane exceeding its critical angle-of-attack and experiencing an aerodynamic stall.

Airport.Name: Blackwell Field
Report.Status: The student pilots failure to maintain control of the airplane during the aborted landing.

Airport.Name: Ann Arbor Municipal
Report.Status: The pilots failure to make a go-around in a timely manner and his loss of control during landing.

Airport.Name: Robertson Field
Report.Status: The pilots overflight of the landing runway during a forced landing after a loss of engine power. Contributing to the accident was the pilots inadequate preflight which resulted in his failure to detect water contamination of the fuel system.
The pilot's improper fuel planning which resulted in a loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion.

Airport.Name: Truckee-Tahoe Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain aircraft control during landing in gusting wind conditions.

Airport.Name: James H. Easom Field
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to increase engine power during the descent for landing when instructed to do so by the flight instructor and the flight instructor's delayed remedial action, which resulted in collision with a static wire. Contributing to the accident was the student pilot's failure to use hearing amplification as required by his Federal Aviation Administration medical certificate.

Airport.Name: Bowman Field
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to set the correct flap position before takeoff and his inadequate preflight planning, which resulted in the operation of the airplane over the maximum allowable gross weight, both of which led to an aerodynamic stall at too low an altitude at which to recover.

Airport.Name: Grand Forks International
Report.Status: The student pilots inadequate recovery from a bounced landing, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall during the go-around.

Airport.Name: Dry Swamp Airport
Report.Status: The inadvertent slippage of the pilot's foot off the right rudder pedal, resulting in a loss of directional control on the ground, and the pilot's overly aggressive application of wheel brakes, resulting in a nose over.

Airport.Name: Flying B Ranch Landing Strip
Report.Status: The pilot's decision to land on a wet grass airstrip, which resulted in a main landing gear collapse after a collision with rough terrain.

A loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion as a result of the pilots inadequate fuel planning. Contributing to the severity of the front passengers injuries was the pilots decision to depart with more passengers than available seats, which resulted in an adult and a child passenger sharing a seatbelt. Contributing to the severity of the rear passengers injuries was the failure of the unapproved modified seat installation.

Airport.Name: Cavanaugh Bay Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain an adequate glide path, which led to a runway excursion and collision with objects.

Airport.Name: Fresno Yosemite International
Report.Status: A hydraulic fluid leak in the nose landing gear actuator rod seal, which prevented the hydraulic system from building up sufficient pressure to fully retract or extend the main landing gear.
The loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination did not reveal any anomalies due to saltwater immersion.

Airport.Name: Dimmit County Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to identify the water contamination of the fuel system during his preflight inspection, which resulted in a total loss of engine power during the airplanes initial climb.

Airport.Name: St Petersburg-Clearwater Intl
Report.Status: A total loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because neither postaccident visual examinations nor test runs of the engine revealed any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Burlington International Airpo
Report.Status: The pilot's improper turn down an airport access road while attempting to taxi to a runway. Contributing to the accident was the airport management's failure to install proper signage indicating that an airport access road was prohibited to aircraft.

Airport.Name: James M Cox Dayton Intn'l
Report.Status: The pilots loss of control of the airplane for reasons that could not be undetermined because a postaccident examination of the airplane did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Cashmere-Dryden
Report.Status: The pilots improper application of the brakes during the landing ground roll, which resulted in a nose over.

Airport.Name: Oakland County International
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to retract the wing flaps before attempting to take off, due to his lack of familiarity with the airplane make and model, which prevented the airplane from maintaining adequate altitude for takeoff.

A loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examinations of the airplane and engine revealed no mechanical malfunctions or failures that would have precluded normal operation.

Airport.Name: Idaho Falls Regional Airport
Report.Status: A loss of power to the right engine during the initial climb due to fuel contamination and the pilot's failure to maintain adequate airspeed and airplane control. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's inadequate preflight check of the airplane.

Airport.Name: Rawlins
Report.Status: The pilots delayed decision to abort the takeoff. Contributing to the accident was the pilot's inadequate preflight planning and a high density altitude, which resulted in a runway excursion and collision with terrain.

Airport.Name: Montgomery Field Airport
Report.Status: Both pilots failure to maintain a proper visual lookout while taxiing during nighttime conditions, which resulted in an on-ground collision.

Airport.Name: El Reno Municipal
Report.Status: A loss of engine power, which resulted from the failure of the magneto assembly for reasons that could not be determined during postaccident examinations.

Airport.Name: Kentmorr Airpark
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the takeoff. Factors in the accident were the pilot's over-rotation at takeoff, and his failure to abort the takeoff prior to the runway excursion.

Airport.Name: Chicago Executive Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper fuel planning and management, which resulted in a loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion.

Airport.Name: Spanish Fork-Springville
Report.Status:
***This report was modified on August 18, 2015. Please see the docket for this accident to view the original report.*** 

The operator's improper installation of a supplemental electrical power supply, which caused a short circuit due to inadequate vibration and abrasion protection, which resulted in chafing of the wires, which contacted one another, short-circuited, and caused an onboard fire. Contributing to the accident were the installation of the supplemental electrical power supply system without the supervision of an FAA-certified mechanic, the lack of an onboard means for fire suppression, and the pilot's inability to see the low-conspicuity power lines across the landing approach path until it was too late to take evasive action.

Airport.Name: Okeechobee County
Report.Status: The student pilots failure to maintain directional control during a go-around.
The airplane's reduced braking efficiency and the pilot's subsequent delayed decision to go around, which resulted in a loss of directional control.

Airport.Name: Yentna River Lodge Airstrip
Report.Status:
The partial loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because the postaccident examination of the engine did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation. 
.

Airport.Name: Fallbrook
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain adequate airspeed during the takeoff, and his loss of aircraft control during the subsequent stall recovery.

Airport.Name: MEMORIAL FIELD
Report.Status: The pilots failure to monitor and manage fuel consumption during cruise flight, which resulted in fuel exhaustion and a subsequent forced landing.

Airport.Name: Miller Airport
Report.Status: The pilots inadequate planning and poor decision to attempt to take off on a runway from which the airplane could not obtain flight.
The pilots failure to maintain directional control of the airplane during landing on a gravel road.
The pilot's loss of situational awareness, which resulted in a wrong turn into a box canyon, and an in flight collision with terrain.

Airport.Name: Private dirt strip
Report.Status: The pilots excessive use of wheel brakes during the takeoff roll, which resulted in a nose-over.

Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll, and the flight instructor's delayed remedial action that resulted in a runway excursion.

Airport.Name: Albany Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The loss of hydraulic fluid, which rendered the brakes ineffective. The reason for the loss of hydraulic fluid could not be determined based on the available evidence.

Airport.Name: Airlake Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's excessive application of the brakes during the landing roll and the flight instructor's delayed remedial action, which resulted in a nose-over.

Report.Status: The student pilots failure to maintain aircraft control during the initial climb, which resulted in a collision with a powerline.

Airport.Name: George Bush Intercontinental
Report.Status: The pilots failure to use the proper taxi procedure, which resulted in a brake system fire.

Airport.Name: Mid-Valley Airport

The pilot's loss of control of the airplane while landing in variable wind conditions.

Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain clearance from trees during final approach due to the sun glare that obscured the pilot's vision.

Airport.Name: Cook airfield
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate compensation for the crosswind, which resulted in a loss of directional control.

Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare and unsuccessful attempt to correct a bounced landing, which resulted in the overrun landing.

Airport.Name: Santa Barbra
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate landing flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Airpark Estates
Report.Status: The pilot did not obtain adequate airspeed and clearance from obstructions during a grass field takeoff.

Airport.Name: Tupelo Regional Airport

Airport.Name: Tappahannock-Essex County

Airport.Name: Shannon Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's intentional descent into the ground to commit suicide.

Airport.Name: South Lake Tahoe
Report.Status: The pilots decision to turn into rising terrain that would have required performance in excess of the airplanes maximum climb rate to clear after taking off at a high density altitude.

Airport.Name: New Smyrna Beach
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper landing flare and subsequent inadequate recovery from a bounced landing.

Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the takeoff roll.

Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing with gusting wind and a quartering tailwind.

Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain adequate clearance from an obstruction while taxiing.

Airport.Name: Burnet Municipal Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper recovery from a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Columbus Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's delayed decision to abort the takeoff. Contributing to the accident was the airplane's perceived lack of performance for reasons that could not be determined due to insufficient information.

Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll, which resulted in a ground loop.

Report.Status: The pilots inadequate landing flare, which resulted in a hard landing and collapse of the left main landing gear.

Airport.Name: Mesquite Metro Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot failed to maintain directional control during the touch-and-go landing and during the subsequent aborted takeoff during crosswind conditions.

Airport.Name: Ellinwood Airport
Report.Status: The pilot failed to maintain directional control during takeoff.

Airport.Name: Private Airstrip
Report.Status: The pilot's improper flare and recovery from a bounced landing and his delay in performing an aborted landing.

Airport.Name: New Bedford Regional
Report.Status: The pilot's improper decision to land in the displaced threshold, resulting in a collision with the approach lighting system.

Airport.Name: West Yellowstone
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the takeoff roll, which resulted in a runway excursion and a collision with an approach slope indicator system component.

Report.Status: The flight instructor's  delayed decision to instruct the pilot to abort the landing which resulted in  a runway excursion and collision with a fence.

Report.Status: The pilots failure to establish and maintain a positive climb rate during the initial climb in night instrument meteorological conditions.

Airport.Name: San Carlos Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll, which resulted in a ground loop.

Report.Status: The pilots inadequate recovery from a bounced landing in crosswind conditions, and an inadvertent aerodynamic stall during the subsequent go-around attempt.

Airport.Name: Portsmouth Intn'l Airport

Airport.Name: Knoxville Downtown Island
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper flare and improper recovery from a bounced landing.

Descent from cruise flight until impact with trees and the ground for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the wreckage did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation and the pilot's autopsy and toxicology tests did not provide any evidence of impairment or incapacitation.

Airport.Name: Camano Island Airfield
Report.Status: The pilots unstabilized approach and his subsequent failure to maintain airspeed during the aborted landing, which resulted in a stall and the airplane bouncing hard on the runway.

Airport.Name: Key Field Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain directional control during the landing roll.

Airport.Name: Allegheny County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper landing flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Crest Airpark
Report.Status: Failure of the certified flight instructor and student pilot to complete the landing checklist resulting in a gear-up landing.

Airport.Name: Robert S. Kerr
Report.Status: The pilots application of excessive left rudder during the takeoff roll, resulting in a loss of directional control, his failure to correct the excursion with opposite rudder, and his failure to abort the takeoff in a timely manner.

Airport.Name: Independence State Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's improper flare with a crosswind condition, and unsuccessful attempt to correct a bounced landing, which resulted in a runway excursion and subsequent nose over.

Airport.Name: Mogollon Airpark
Report.Status: The partial loss of engine power during takeoff due to the separation of the exhaust baffling, which resulted in a partial blockage of airflow. Contributing to the accident was inadequate maintenance of the exhaust system.

Airport.Name: Ernest A. Love Field Airport
Report.Status: The pilots improper flare, which resulted in a hard landing.

Airport.Name: Hesperia Airport
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain sufficient airspeed on final approach to landing which resulted in an inadvertent stall.
The pilot's loss of directional control during takeoff.
The partial loss of engine power due to a loose throttle cable clamp.

Airport.Name: SULLIVAN LAKE STATE
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to maintain clearance from a windsock pole while taxiing.

Airport.Name: Sleetmute Airport
Report.Status: The total loss of engine power due to fuel starvation and the pilot's inadequate preflight inspection.

Airport.Name: Goose Creek
Report.Status: The pilot's improper preflight planning, which resulted in a total loss of engine power due to fuel exhaustion.
The improper routing of the seatbelt, which resulted in the inadvertent deployment of the reserve parachute, and the open jump door, which allowed the passenger to be pulled from the airplane.
The pilot's failure to maintain directional control during landing.

Airport.Name: Greater Kankakee
Report.Status: The airplane struck a deer during takeoff. Contributing to the accident was the perimeter fence being less than FAA's recommended 10 feet high.

Airport.Name: Charles B. Wheeler Downtown
Report.Status: The pilot's improper decision to attempt continued flight after a momentary loss of engine power with usable runway remaining. Contributing to the accident were the pilot's premature retraction of the landing gear, the loss of engine power due to fuel system water contamination, and the pilot's failure to detect the fuel contamination during the preflight inspection.

Airport.Name: Chicago Executive
Report.Status: The pilots loss of control due to the passengers inadvertent application of left rudder during the takeoff roll.

Airport.Name: Summit Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots improper recovery from a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Gadabout Gaddis
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate preflight planning, which resulted in his attempt to take off from a short, turf runway in high-density altitude conditions under which the airplane was unable to attain a positive climb rate to clear trees.

Airport.Name: Indianapolis Executive
Report.Status: The pilot's inadequate monitoring on the airplane's airspeed during the go-around, resulting in a stall.

Airport.Name: Manassas Regional Airport
Report.Status: The student pilots improper recovery from a bounced landing.

Airport.Name: Boise Air Terminal
Report.Status: The mechanical failure of the nose landing gear for reasons that could not be determined because impact damage prevented a complete examination.

Airport.Name: Easton/Newman Field
Report.Status: The use of an improper nose landing gear through bolt, which decreased the overall strength of the gear and resulted in overload failure during a hard landing. Contributing to the accident was the student pilot's inadequate landing flare, which resulted in the hard landing.

Airport.Name: Merrill Field Airport

Airport.Name: Private

Airport.Name: Marco Island
Report.Status: The pilots improper pitch trim setting before takeoff, which resulted in the airplanes rapid, nose-high pitch at takeoff and the pilots subsequent loss of control.

Airport.Name: Freeway Airport
Report.Status: The pilots decision to depart with a known deficiency following a hard landing. Contributing to the accident was an anomaly of the airplanes nosewheel steering that could not be replicated during post-accident examination.

Airport.Name: Taunton Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot/owners inadequate preflight inspection and inadequate pretakeoff check of the flight controls, which resulted in a takeoff with the rudder gust lock installed. Airport.Name: Klenawicus Airfield
Report.Status: The pilot did not attain the proper touchdown point on the runway, which resulted in a runway excursion.

Airport.Name: Kendall-Tamiami Airport
Report.Status: The pilots incapacitation due to a seizure during taxi.

Airport.Name: Edgar County Airport
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to abort the takeoff during the ground roll after detecting the airplane's degraded performance. Airport.Name: Breezecroft Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's improper control inputs which resulted in a loss of control and aerodynamic stall. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor's delayed remedial action.

Airport.Name: MERRILL FIELD
Report.Status: The pilot's loss of control of the airplane during takeoff, resulting in a ground loop.

Airport.Name: Danville Regional Airport
Report.Status: The student pilot's failure to maintain control and climb the airplane during a go-around maneuver. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor's failure to provide adequate oversight of the student pilot by ensuring that the cockpit was free of distractions.

The pilots failure to maintain airplane control while maneuvering at low altitude, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall/spin and collision with terrain. Contributing to the accident was the pilots use of marijuana, which likely degraded his psychomotor ability.

Airport.Name: Fort Lauderdale Executive
Report.Status: The student pilots failure to apply power to go-around following a bounced landing resulting in abnormal runway contact and collapse of the nose landing gear.

Airport.Name: Limington-Harmon Airport

Airport.Name: MC COMB/PIKE COUNTY/JOHN E LEW
Report.Status: The pilots failure to maintain adequate airspeed during approach to landing, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall and subsequent loss of control.

Airport.Name: Boulder Municipal
Report.Status: The pilot's failure to adequately clear carburetor icing, resulting in a loss of engine power on final approach following a descent at idle power.

Airport.Name: PHOENIX DEER VALLEY
Report.Status: The student pilot's inadequate flare and the flight instructor's delayed remedial action and failure to maintain control of the airplane during a go-around. Contributing to the accident was the flight instructor's improper go-around procedures.
The pilot's decision to take off from a remote, rough landing site in gusty wind conditions, which resulted in a loss of control.

Airport.Name: Private
Report.Status: The pilot's delay in aborting the landing which resulted in the airplane contacting the terrain off the departure end of the runway.

Airport.Name: Council Bluffs Municipal
Report.Status: The student pilot's loss of directional control during takeoff.
The pilot's decision to conduct a precautionary landing following a loss of altitude during takeoff initial climb.
The pilots failure to maintain adequate airspeed while maneuvering at a low altitude, which resulted in an aerodynamic stall/spin and impact with the ground.

Airport.Name: Gallup Municipal Airport

The pilot's delayed decision to go-around, which resulted in a collision with water.

Airport.Name: LONG BEACH /DAUGHERTY FIELD/

Undetermined because the pilot and airplane were not found.

Airport.Name: VICTORIA RGNL

Airport.Name: Princeton Municipal Airport
Report.Status: An in-flight collision with a bald eagle.

Airport.Name: Casa Grande Municipal Airport
Report.Status: A loss of engine power during final approach for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examinations did not reveal any anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.
The pilot's inadvertent encounter with a mound while landing on a remote airstrip.

Airport.Name: ELY ARPT /YELLAND FLD/
Report.Status: The pilots failure to monitor the environment, which led to a collision with power lines during climbout. Contributing to the accident was the loss of engine power during low-altitude flight for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examination of the airframe and engine did not reveal any mechanical malfunctions or failures that would have precluded normal operation, which led to a forced landing that the pilot subsequently aborted when the engine regained full power.

Airport.Name: WM 'TINY' ZEHNDER FIELD
Report.Status: An intermittent loss of engine power for reasons that could not be determined because postaccident examinations revealed no anomalies that would have precluded normal operation.
